This paper addresses a data-driven input reconstruction problem based on
Willems' Fundamental Lemma. The corresponding unknown input estimator (UIE) is
constructed directly from historical data. Given the output measurement, the
estimated input by the UIE asymptotically converges to the actual input without
knowing the initial conditions. The necessary and sufficient existence
conditions of such a UIE are provided. Two design methods are elaborated based
on the Lyapunov condition and generalized inverse of Hankel matrices. Finally,
the proposed data-driven UIE is validated by both simulation and experiment.
\end{abstract}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{INTRODUCTION}
The input reconstruction problem has intrigued the control community for decades
with applications in system supervision, sensor fault detection and robust
control~\cite{hou1998input,ansari2018input,tokutake2012disturbance,rajamani2017o
bservers}. In such a problem, the output of a so called unknown input estimator
(UIE) converge to the unknown input of the original system while the original
output measurement is given but the initial system condition is unknown.
In~\cite{hou1998input}, input observaility is defined to check the existence
condition of the estimater for LTI system, and a systematic design approach is
given based on a matrix pencil decomposition form. \cite{moylan1977stable}
propose to find stable inverse system for input reconstruction and define the
necessary and sufficient conditions for stable invertibility.
More recently, simultaneous unknown input reconstruction and state estimation
are achieved by unknown input observer
(UIO)~\cite{valcher1999state,sundaram2007delayed}, optimal
filters~\cite{gillijns2007unbiased, yong2015simultaneous}, generalized inverse
approach~\cite{ansari2019deadbeat} and sliding mode
observers~\cite{zhu2012state}. In~\cite{valcher1999state}, an elegant design
procedure is proposed to design a full-order UIO. Given the estimated state by
UIO, the input estimate can be computed by matrix inversion and converge to the
actual input along with the state convergence. ~\cite{ansari2019deadbeat}
utilizes the generalized matrix for simultaneous state estimation and input
reconstruction and the estimation is achieved in a finite number of steps.
All the above work assumes the system model is given. Therefore a step of system
identification should be performed before the design of the input
reconstruction.
As an alternative to the above two-step workflow, we utilize the behavioral
theory to directly design an unknown input estimator from data in this work.
The Williems' Fundamental Lemma is such a method that describe the trajectory of
LTI system based on historical measured input and output
signals~\cite{willems2005note}.

Data-driven input reconstructionJicheng Shi, Yingzhao Lian, and Colin N. JonesAbstract— This paper addresses a data-driven input recon-struction problem based on Willems’ Fundemental Lemma. Thecorresponding unknown input estimator (UIE) is constructeddirectly from historical data. Given the output measurement,the estimated input by the UIE asymptotically converges tothe actual input without knowing the initial conditions. Thenecessary and sufficient existence conditions of such a UIE areprovided. Two design methods are elaborated based on theLyapnov condition and generalized inverse of Hankel matrices.Finally, the proposed data-driven UIE is validated by bothsimulation and experiment.I. INTRODUCTIONThe input reconstruction problem has intrigued the controlcommunity for decades with applications in system supervi-sion, sensor fault detection and robust control [1], [2], [3],[4]. In such a problem, the output of a so called unknowninput estimator (UIE) converge to the unknown input of theoriginal system while the original output measurement isgiven but the initial system condition is unknown. In [1],input observaility is defined to check the existence conditionof the estimater for LTI system, and a systematic designapproach is given based on a matrix pencil decompositionform. [5] propose to find stable inverse system for inputreconstruction and define the necessary and sufficient condi-tions for stable invertibility.More recently, simultaneous unknown input reconstructionand state estimation are achieved by unknown input observer(UIO) [6], [7], optimal filters [8], [9], generalized inverseapproach [10] and sliding mode observers [11]. In [6], anelegant design procedure is proposed to design a full-orderUIO. Given the estimated state by UIO, the input estimatecan be computed by matrix inversion and converge to theactual input along with the state convergence. [10] utilizesthe generalized matrix for simultaneous state estimation andinput reconstruction and the estimation is achieved in a finitenumber of steps.All the above work assumes the system model is given.Therefore a step of system identification should be performedbefore the design of the input reconstruction. As an alterna-tive to the above two-step workflow, we utilize the behavioraltheory to directly design an unknown input estimator fromdata in this work. The Williems’ Fundamental Lemma is sucha method that describe the trajectory of LTI system basedThis work has received support from the Swiss National Science Founda-tion under the RISK project (Risk Aware Data-Driven Demand Response),grant number 200021 175627.JichengShi,YingzhaoLianandColinN.JonesarewithAutomaticLaboratory,EcolePolytechniqueFederaledeLausanne,Switzerland.{jicheng.shi, yingzhao.lian,colin.jones}@epfl.chon historical measured input and output signals [12]. Thisdescription provides a convenient interface to data-drivenoutput prediction [13] and different controller design [14],[15], [16], [17], [18]. In [19], the authors build a data-drivenUIO based on historical state, unknown input and outputdata. Our work is distinguish from it with a specific focus oninput reconstruction. Furthermore, we claim some freedom todesign the data-driven UIE and two specific design procedurewill be presented. We also validate the proposed methodby the experiment results of occupancy estimation by themeasurement of indoor carbon-dioxide level.In the following, the output prediction based on Willems’fundamental lemma is reviewed and the target unknown inputestimator is defined in Section II. In Section III, the sufficientand necessary existence condition of the data-driven UIE isgiven. In addition, two specific design methods to build sucha UIE are proposed. In Section IV, the results of a simplesimulation and a experimental application are presented. Itconcludes the paper and provide some future potentials inSection V.NotationLetnMandmMrespectively denote the numbers of rowand column of a matrixM∈RnM×mM. \begin{subequations} \label{eqn:output_pred}
\begin{align}
\begin{bmatrix}
\Han_{L,init}(u_\textbf{d}) \\ \Han_{L,init}(y_\textbf{d}) \\\Han_{L,pred}(u_\textbf{d})
\end{bmatrix} g &=
\begin{bmatrix}
u_{t-N_{init}+1:t}\\
y_{t-N_{init}+1:t}\\
u_{t+1:t+N_{pred}}
\end{bmatrix} \label{eqn:output_pred_1}\\
\Han_{L,pred}(y_\textbf{d}) &=:y_{t+1:t+N_{pred}} \label{eqn:output_pred_2}
\end{align}
\end{subequations}
in which two sub-Hankel matrices of output comes from the separation:
\begin{align}
\Han_L(y_\textbf{d}) = \begin{bmatrix}
\Han_{L,init}(y_\textbf{d})\\\Han_{L,pred}(y_\textbf{d})
\end{bmatrix}\;. \label{eqn:Han_sep}
\end{align}
The depth of two matrices are $N_{init}$ and $N_{pred}$ respectively, such that $N_{init} + N_{pred} = L$. The Hankel matrices $\Han_{L,init}
    (u_\textbf{d})$ are constructed similarly.
At time $t$, $N_{init}$-step previous trajectory $[ u_{t-N_{init}+1:t}; y_{t-N_{init}+1:t}]$. For any given $N_{pred}$-step future input $u_{t+1:t
    +N_{pred}}$, the solution of the decision variable $g$ is computed by~\eqref{eqn:output_pred_1}. Then the $N_{pred}$-step future output is
    predicted by~\eqref{eqn:output_pred_2}. In the prediction workflow, it chooses $N_{init} \geq \mathbf{l}(\mathcal{B}(A,B,C,D))$, for the reason of a
    unique initial state determination. Readers are referred to~\cite{markovsky2008data} for more details.
\subsection{Problem formulation}
In this work, we aim to construct a data-driven method to estimate input by measured output based on the Ffundamental \textit{Lemma}~\ref{lem:funda}. It
    assumes that output $y_t$ is always measurable but the input $u_t$ can only be measured offline. Measurable inputs are omitted for simplicity, which
    does not affect the generality of the discussion.
In industry, some input can be measured offline by laboratory experiments but is unrealistic or very expensive to be measured on line, such as the
    cutting foce of exerted by the machine tool~\cite{zhu2012state}. In the building community, the occupant number is a key factor for human comfort
    satisfaction and building energy simulation and control~\cite{chen2018building}. However, some occupancy detection tools, such as camera and Wifi,
    suffers from privacy issues. Thus, our motivation comes from occupancy estimation by the indoor CO2 level after a limited size of historical
    occupancy dataset is collected.
Given some measured $N_{init}$-step initial trajectory and the $N_{est}$-step output measurements, the input $u_t$ can be computed by
\begin{subequations}\label{eqn:input_est}
\begin{align}
\begin{bmatrix}
\Han_{L,init}(u_\textbf{d}) \\ \Han_{L,init}(y_\textbf{d}) \\\Han_{L,est}(y_\textbf{d})
\end{bmatrix} g &=
\begin{bmatrix}
u_{t-N_{init}:t-1}\\
y_{t-N_{init}+1:t-1}\\
y_{t:t+N_{est}-1}
\end{bmatrix} \label{eqn:input_est_1}\\
\Han_{L,est(1)}(u_\textbf{d})g &=:u_{t} \label{eqn:input_est_2}
\end{align}
\end{subequations}
The sub-Hankel matrices come from the separation similar to~\eqref{eqn:Han_sep} so that $N_{ini}+N_{est} = L$.
But $\Han_{L,est(1)}(u_\textbf{d})$ is first $n_u$ rows of $\Han_{L,est}(u_\textbf{d})$ and only one input is estimated in~\eqref{eqn:input_est_2}.
    Apart from $N_{init}\geq\mathbf{l}(\mathcal{B}(A,B,C,D))$, the choices of $N_{est}$ for output measurement depends on the properties of matrices
    $\{B,C,D\}$ in the system~\eqref{eqn:lin_dyn_deter}. For example, if $D$ is full column rank, the single input $y_{t}$ will determine a unique input
    $u_{t}$ after the behind state $x_{t+1}$ is uniquely estimated by $N_{init}$ steps.
